ely EOF for the pipeline.\n\nSo the issue is that `echo      ` in PowerShell is parsed as `echo` with no arguments (spaces are ignored), which produces no output → EOF → `getline` fails.\n\nFor an empty line test, the user needs:\n- `echo \"\" | program.exe` in PowerShell — sends empty string (a `\\n`), getline succeeds with empty string\n- `type nul | program.exe` — sends nothing, getline fails\n\nFor the test spec from task 2:\n- **EOF test (66):** `type nul | prog`\n- **Empty name test (65):** `echo \"\" | prog` — but only if name is first, then needs `\\n5` for the second line\n\nWait, but the second input needs the number. So:\n- `echo \"\" | echo 5 | ...` doesn't chain in cmd.\n- Better: `(echo \"\" & echo 5) | prog` in PowerShell... actually, `&` is different in PowerShell.\n  \nIn PowerShell:\n- `\"\" | prog` — sends empty string\n- But for two lines, pipe chains are complex. Better to use a here-string or an input file.\n\nActually, for the empty name test, the input would be:\n```\n<empty line>\n5\n```\n\nIn cmd:\n```\n(echo; & echo 5) | t2_passport_cpp\\main.exe\n```\n\nIn PowerShell:\n```\n\"\",\n5 | t2_passport_cpp\\main.exe\n```\n\nHmm, actually in PowerShell, comma-separated values on the pipeline would send each element separately. The newline between them might not be what we want.\n\nLet me think about this more practically. The bat test file already works in cmd. Let me focus on what the user needs.\n\nThe user's specific question: why does `echo      ` produce EOF?\n\nAnswer: In PowerShell, `echo      ` with only spaces after it parses as `echo` (Write-Output) with no arguments (spaces are trimmed parameter separation), which produces **no output at all** → pipe sees nothing → stdin is immediately at EOF → `getline` returns `false` → EOF case.",
